    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-01-13T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-01-13T16:00:00-05:00" n="256"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d256">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/611: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DJW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Davis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-01-13T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 13, 1919, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4037. Repeat to Paris and Rome. Am[erican] mission being advised direct.
                    Referring to Department’s No. 3991, Jan. 10 [<hi rend="italic">9</hi>], 7
                        p.m.<note n="33" xml:id="d256fn33">Not printed; it communicated the text of
                        telegram from the Ambassador in Japan, Dec. 27, 1918, 10 p.m. (<ref
                            target="frus1918Russiav03#pg_301">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1918, Russia, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 301</ref>), which telegram contained
                        the text of railway plan printed <hi rend="italic">infra.</hi>
                    </note> Following telegram from Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MRS1"
                        >Morris</persName> at Tokio, January 9, 12 midnight, gives final status of
                    railway negotiations. The Department is authorizing Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MRS1">Morris</persName> to proceed to Vladivostok in the near
                    future to settle preliminary arrangements and has told him that he and <persName
                        corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName> can go ahead with the plan as soon as
                    we notify him that Japanese Ambassador at Washington has presented the matter
                    formally to this Government, at which time we will also instruct you to give
                    formal notification to the government to which you are accredited. In the
                    meanwhile please keep the government to which you are accredited fully advised,
                    orally, of the status of the situation to date.</p>
                <p>[Here follows text of telegram from the Ambassador in Japan, January 9, 12
                    midnight, with final sentence omitted, printed <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref
                        target="#pg_236">p. 236</ref>.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PFL">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
